We must first determine which transactions “contribute” to tax expense. In our model sales records carry a “tax_amount” column. (Other entries such as expense, purchase and depreciation do not affect the tax expense item.) So we go through every transaction whose type is “Sale” and then add together the amounts in the “tax_amount” field.

For the new problem table the sales rows and their tax amounts are:

1. Sale20240106004: tax_amount = 37,404.36  
2. Sale20240111008: tax_amount = 57,566.83  
3. Sale20240114010: tax_amount = 34,677.31  
4. Sale20240119016: tax_amount = 67,403.41  
5. Sale20240122019: tax_amount = 34,732.89  
6. Sale20240123021: tax_amount = 53,802.71  
7. Sale20240124022: tax_amount = 33,868.23  
8. Sale20240125024: tax_amount = 110,529.26  
9. Sale20240126025: tax_amount = 33,079.03  
10. Sale20240130031: tax_amount = 74,643.53  
11. Sale20240131033: tax_amount = 35,893.21  
12. Sale20240202035: tax_amount = 33,048.49  
13. Sale20240204038: tax_amount = 105,460.80

Now, we add them step by step:

• 37,404.36 + 57,566.83 = 94,971.19  
• 94,971.19 + 34,677.31 = 129,648.50  
• 129,648.50 + 67,403.41 = 197,051.91  
• 197,051.91 + 34,732.89 = 231,784.80  
• 231,784.80 + 53,802.71 = 285,587.51  
• 285,587.51 + 33,868.23 = 319,455.74  
• 319,455.74 + 110,529.26 = 429,985.00  
• 429,985.00 + 33,079.03 = 463,064.03  
• 463,064.03 + 74,643.53 = 537,707.56  
• 537,707.56 + 35,893.21 = 573,600.77  
• 573,600.77 + 33,048.49 = 606,649.26  
• 606,649.26 + 105,460.80 = 712,110.06  

The total tax expense is therefore 712,110.06. This is the amount that would be reported as “Tax Expense” on the income statement.

Thus, our final answer is:
